*A HashMap in Java is part of the java.util package.
->It stores data in key–value pairs, allowing you to:
->Access values using their keys
->Avoid duplicates in keys
->Allow one null key and multiple null values

ex: import java.util.HashMap;

    public class Example{
        public static void main (String args[]){
            HashMap<Integer,String> map = new HashMap<>();
            map.put(1,"Sandesh");
            map.put(2,"Developer");
            map.put(3,"Web");

            System.out.println(map)
        }
    }


put(key, value) — Add or Update
    HashMap<Integer, String> map = new HashMap<>();
    map.put(1, "Java");
    map.put(2, "Python");
    map.put(3, "C++");
    System.out.println(map);


get(key) — Retrieve Value
    System.out.println(map.get(2)); // Spring
    System.out.println(map.get(5)); // null (not found)

remove(key) — Delete Key–Value Pair
    map.remove(3);
    System.out.println(map); // {1=Java, 2=Spring}

containsKey(key) / containsValue(value)
    System.out.println(map.containsKey(1));   // true
    System.out.println(map.containsValue("Java")); // true


System.out.println(map.size()); // 2
System.out.println(map.isEmpty()); // false
map.clear();
System.out.println(map); // {}
